        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 77-year-old retired civil engineer who spent 35 years designing bridges and urban infrastructure before stepping down a decade ago. He is a widower who lives alone in a modest single-story home on the outskirts of a mid-sized Midwestern city, having adapted his living space with grab bars, non-slip flooring, and a walk-in shower following several near-falls. His two adult children live in nearby cities and check in regularly, and a home health aide visits three times per week to assist with meal preparation and personal care.\n\nOnce an avid woodworker and amateur chess player, {patientName} now struggles to hold his carving tools steady and finds that the slow, deliberate thinking required for chess has become increasingly frustrating. He occasionally listens to jazz records and enjoys the company of his neighbor, who brings him homemade meals twice a week. He is a non-smoker and drinks only a small glass of red wine on special occasions.\n\nOn examination, {patientName} presents with a classic Parkinsonian resting tremor in his right hand (\"pill-rolling\"), bilateral cogwheel rigidity most prominent in the upper extremities, and marked bradykinesia. His posture is stooped with a slightly flexed trunk, and his gait is shuffling with reduced arm swing and occasional festination. His facial expression is hypomimic, giving him a characteristic \"masked face,\" and his speech is notably hypophonic and monotone.\n\n{patientName} reports significant difficulty with fine motor tasks such as buttoning his shirt and writing, both of which have deteriorated considerably over the past two years. He experiences moderate episodes of \"off\" periods in the late morning, typically 30–40 minutes before his next levodopa dose, during which tremor and rigidity worsen considerably. He also reports orthostatic lightheadedness when rising from a chair, constipation, and intermittent urinary urgency — all autonomic features consistent with his condition.\n\nHe sleeps poorly, often awakening during the night with vivid dreams and occasional acting-out behaviors consistent with REM sleep behavior disorder. His mood is generally stoic, though he admits to episodes of low mood and mild anxiety about his increasing dependence on others. Cognitively, he remains oriented and communicates clearly, though he notices mild slowing in his word retrieval and short-term memory."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
